@node FROM "From"

        The name of who sends the message.
@endnode
@node TO "To"

        The name of who receives the message.
@endnode
@node SUBJ "Subj"

        The subject of the message.
@endnode
@node FILE "File"

        The ASCII text file you wish to import to you message.
@endnode
@node TAGN "Tagn"

        This  option applies only to public messages for Echomail
        conferences.   You  can  here  specify the TAGNAME of the
        conference you wish to put the message into.
@endnode
@node ORIGL "Origl"

        Again,   this   option   only   makes   sense  if  you're
        broadcasting  Echomail  messages.   This is your system's
        origin  line.  Make sure it does not exceed the 80 column
        limit  and remember that PktGen will add the ' * Origin:'
        conference  mail  message  control  information  and  the
        address of your system to it.  This way, the final origin
        line will look something like this:

          * Origin: My System's Origin Line (2:361/9.1)
@endnode
@node MDIR "MDir"

        This  is the directory were you want PktGen to create the
        packets.   If  you  wish  to send EchoMail, use something
        like  'Mail:InBound'  so  that  your  system  mailer  can
        distribute the message to all the nodes you feed.  If you
        want  to  send  private  NetMail,  I suggest you use your
        Outbound  directory (Ex:  Mail:OutBound) and if you want,
        make use of the @{"UPDATEFLO" link UPDATEFLO} feature (See above).
@endnode
@node CONF "Conf"

        You   can   override  the  default  Monalisa:Preferences/
        configuration  file  with  this argument.  (See above for
        details about the @{"configuration file" link CONFIGFILE}).
@endnode
@node PKT "PKT"

        Useful  if  PKTGen is about to create lots of messages in
        the InBound Directory.  This way you can specify the name
        of  the  file  where  you wish the messages to be stored.
        Instead  of  many  files you'll have only a big file with
        all messages inside. See also the @{"NOTLAST" link NOTLAST} flag.
@endnode
@node NOTLAST "NotLast"

        Should  be  used in conjunction with the @{"PKT" link PKT} parameter.
        This tells PKTGen that the packet in which the message in
        going  to be stored will not be closed.  The last message
        you  wish  to  store  in  the  packet  must have the flag
        disabled  otherwise  many mailers may consider the packet
        as corrupt and thus, move it to BAD.
@endnode
@node OA "OA/DA"

        The  origin   /  destination address of the message.  You
        can  enter  addresses  in the old 3D or the new 4D format
        with  or  without  domain.   Examples  are:   OA=2:361/9,
        OA=2:361/9.1, OA=2:361/9.1@FidoNet.
@endnode
@node QUIET "Quiet"

        There will be no output to std.  output while packets are
        being generated.
@endnode
@node NOLF "NoLF"

        PktGen  will  NOT  attempt  to  convert  CRs  to  LFs for
        compatibility with IBM standards.  This is unnecessary in
        most  cases  and  by  disabling the CR conversion you are
        speeding up the process.  NOLF is advisable when you have
        huge  amounts  of  messages  to  create  and  have a slow
        machine working on it.
@endnode
@node NETMAIL "NetMail"

        Use  this  flag  if  you're  sending  a  private  netmail
        message.   This  will  omit  all  conference mail message
        control  information  and activate the MSGPRIVATE flag in
        the  packet  header.  It will also add the INTL, FMPT and
        TOPT lines to the message body.
@endnode
@node UPDATEFLO "UpdateFLO"

        Files  in  the  Outbound  directory  that  have  the .FLO
        extension  are  used  by  FrontDoors  to determinate what
        files  will  be  sent  to  a  specific site during a mail
        session.   If  you're  using  PktGen  to  create  netmail
        messages  or  even echomail, you may wish to update those
        FLO  files by adding the name of the file containing your
        message   to  them.   The  method  that  PktGen  uses  to
        determinate the FLO filename is:  zone.net.node.point.FLO
        from  the  destination address.  Most FrontDoors use this
        format,  including the popular TrapDoor.  If you're using
        another  FrontDoor  that  requires a different format for
        the FLO control files, send me detailed information and I
        will create an upgrade supporting those formats.
@endnode
@node MSGLOCAL "MSGLocal"

        This  is  a  flag  that is included in main struture of a
        mail  packet  when  a message in entered locally and it's
        not  NetMail.   I've  included  this  option because some
        mailers  interpret  this  flag  wrong.  A good example is
        XMail  from  Excelsior  that  turns  these  messages into
        NetMail  is  the  flag  is on (V.1.42).  So, if you don't
        really need this flag, leave it off and no-one gets hurt.
@endnode
@node CONFIGFILE "ConfigFile"

        When  you run PktGen without arguments, it searches for a
        file  called  PktGen.prefs that should be present in your
        MONALISA:Preferences/  directory.   A  configuration file
        must look like this:

         SysOp
         All
         System Report
         s:Startup-Sequence
         AMY_CRAP
         System's Origin Line 
         Mail:InBound/
         2:361/9.0
         2:361/9.0
         etcelso@zeus.ua.pt

         # PKTGen Default Environment Information
         #
         # Line 1  - From Whom
         # Line 2  - To Who
         # Line 3  - Message Subject
         # Line 4  - Message File
         # Line 5  - Echo TAGNAME
         # Line 6  - Origin Line
         # Line 7  - Storage Dir
         # Line 8  - Origin Address 
         # Line 9  - Destination Address 
         # Line 10 - E-Mail Reply Address

        Optionally,  you  can also use a configuration file other
        than    the    one    that    must    be    present    in
        MONALISA:Preferences/  using the CONF argument as long as
        the  format  remains  the  same.  In both cases, PktGen's
        arguments will always override these settings.
@endnode
@node REPLYADDR "E-Mail Reply Address"

        If  you are gating messages from the Internet to Fidonet,
        this  kludge  will  give  the  information to the Fidonet
        software of the E-Mail address from the origin user.  You
        may  define a default REPLYADDR in the @{"configuration file" link CONFIGFILE}
        or use command line argument.

        Example:

        PKTGen REPLYADDR=etcelso@zeus.ua.pt

        See also @{"NOREPLYADDR" link NOREPLYADDR}
@endnode
@node NOREPLYADDR "NoReplyAddress"

        If  this  flag  is set, PKTGen will not add the REPLYADDR
        kludge to your Echomail/Netmail messages.  This is useful
        for system that don't have any Internet E-Mail access.
@endnode
@node MSGPRIVATE "MSGPRIVATE flag."

        This  flag  sets  the  MSGPRIVATE  bit in packet headers.
        This  allows  to create private messages in public echos.
        Warning:    In   some  fidonet  networks/zones,  this  is
        agaisn't  policy.   Check  with you HUB before using this
        flag.
@endnode
